    Introduction

    <div align:left>In this notebook, Data Science project Data scraping and visulization of data is displayed.

    Some of the popular libraries that we used for Data Extraction using python are:</div>



    1. Yfinance - Stock data libraries


    2. plotly - plot the infromation, visualizations


    3. bs4 - Structuring the raw data


    4. Pandas - for data manipulation and analysis in Python


    5. request - factching the data from website

    ANS 1: Using the yfinance Library to Extract Tesla's Stock Data

    ¶

    Using the Ticker module we can create an object that will allow us to access functions to extract data. To do this we need to provide the ticker symbol for the stock, here the company is TESLA and the ticker symbol is TSLA.

    In [ ]:
    tesla = yf.Ticker("TSLA")

    Extracting Share Price

    A share is the single smallest part of a company's stock that you can buy, the prices of these shares fluctuate over time. Using the history() function, Set the period parameter to max so we get information for the maximum amount of time.

    In [ ]:
    tesla_data=tesla.history(period="max")

    Reset the index using the reset_index(inplace=True) function on the tesla_data DataFrame and display the first five rows of the tesla_data dataframe using the head function.

    In [ ]:
    tesla_data.reset_index(inplace=True)
tesla_data.head()
    Out[ ]:
    Date Open High Low Close Volume Dividends Stock Splits

    The format that the data is returned in is a Pandas DataFrame. With the Date as the index the share Open, High, Low, Close, Volume, and Stock Splits are given for each day.

    Now we can access functions and variables to extract the type of data we need. You can view them and what they represent here https://aroussi.com/post/python-yahoo-finance.

    In [ ]:
    tesla_info=tesla.info

    Ans 2: Useing Webscraping to Extract Tesla's Revenue Data

    ¶

    Use the requests library to download the webpage https://www.macrotrends.net/stocks/charts/TSLA/tesla/revenue. Save the text of the response as a variable named html_data.

    In [ ]:
    url = "https://backlinko.com/tesla-stats"
html_data = requests.get(url).text

    Parse the html data using beautiful_soup.

    In [ ]:
    soup=BeautifulSoup(html_data,"html5lib")
print(soup.prettify)

ul{margin-top:0!important;}.css-wsmnt ul li{line-height:32px;}</style><div class="css-wsmnt" id="content"><p>Tesla was incorporated as an electric vehicle manufacturer in July 2003.</p>
<p>Initially, the company faced significant difficulties when it came to developing technology, producing prototypes, and scaling manufacturing. Elon Musk joined the company as chairman in 2004. Early on, he stated that Tesla had just a 10% chance of success.</p>
<p>Despite the major hurdles encountered, the company produced its one-millionth car in March 2020.</p>
<p>Today, Tesla delivers more than 200,000 vehicles each quarter, with plans to ramp up production significantly in the future.</p>
<p>From revenue to the number of charging stations, here’s a breakdown of everything you’ll find out about on this page:</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="key-tesla-stats">Key Tesla Stats</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tesla has sold <b>473,136</b> electric cars in the first 8 months of 2021. More than any other electric vehicle manufacturer worldwide.</li>
<li>Since 2009, Tesla has produced a total of <strong>1.91 million</strong> vehicles.</li>
<li>Tesla has manufactured <b>386,759</b> vehicles in the first two quarters of 2021 alone.</li>
<li>Tesla’s revenue in Q1 + Q2 2021 was<strong><b>$22.35 billion</b></strong>.</li>
<li><strong>70,757 employees</strong> work at Tesla worldwide.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-vehicle-deliveries">Tesla vehicle deliveries</h2>
<p>In the first six months of 2021, Tesla delivered <strong><b>184,877</b> vehicles</strong> in Q1 and <b>201,304 vehicles</b> in Q2. This represents a year over year growth of over 121%.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-vehicle-production">Tesla vehicle production</h2>
<p>Tesla also produced over <b>200,000 vehicles</b> in Q2 2021. This was the first quarter that Tesla has both produced and delivered over 200,000 vehicles. Vehicle production in Q2 shows a year over year growth of an impressive 151%.</p>

<p>Tesla’s annual vehicle production has increased <b>5.06x</b> from 2017 to 2020.  For perspective, it took the company <b>181 days</b> to manufacture 50,000 Tesla vehicles in 2017. Today, the same number of vehicles can be produced in just <b>36 days</b>.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="total-teslas-sold">Total Teslas Sold</h2>
<p>According to Tesla investor reports, <strong>Tesla has sold 1,917,450 electric vehicles to date.</strong></p>
<p>Interestingly, 32% of all Teslas sold since 2016 have been sold so far in 2021.</p>
<p>Source: <a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/502208/tesla-quarterly-vehicle-deliveries/" rel="noopener" target="_blank" title="Statista">Statista</a></p>
<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-annual-revenue">Tesla annual revenue</h2>
<p>In 2020, Tesla generated <strong>$31.54 billion</strong> in annual revenue. That’s an increase of <strong>28.31%</strong> compared to 2019. In the first six months of 2021, Tesla’s revenue is already <b>$22.35 billion.</b></p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-supercharger-locations">Tesla Supercharger locations</h2>
<p>Supercharger is Tesla’s fast-charging network.</p>
<p>Tesla operates <strong>3,059</strong> Supercharger stations in over 40 countries as of October 2021. The number of Supercharger locations has increased by <strong>86.07%</strong> over the last two years (July 2019 – July 2021).</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-supercharger-stations-by-country">Tesla Supercharger stations by country</h2>
<p>As of October 2021, the US and China account for <strong>65.54%</strong> of all Tesla Supercharger stations. The two countries contain a combined <strong>2005</strong> Supercharger locations.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-manufacturing-facilities">Tesla manufacturing facilities</h2>
<p>Tesla has <strong>6 manufacturing facilities</strong> spanning 3 countries: the United States, China and Germany.</p>
<p><strong>4</strong> of Tesla’s plants are already in operation. As well as the original Fremont Factory in California, there are active production lines at the Gigafactory Nevada, Gigafactory New York and Gigafactory Shanghai.</p>
<p>As of June 2021, the remaining 2 facilities (Gigafactory Berlin and Gigafactory Texas) are under construction.</p>
<p>Across its Fremont and Shanghai locations, Tesla has an installed annual production capacity of <strong>1.05 million</strong> vehicles.</p>
<p><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://ir.tesla.com/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="Tesla">Tesla</a></p>
<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-worldwide-sales">Tesla’s worldwide sales</h2>
<p>Tesla sold <strong>499,535</strong> vehicles in 2020, making it the most popular EV manufacturer. This year, Tesla has outsold  SAIC-GM-Wuling, its closest competitor, by <strong>77.06%</strong>. By the end of August 2021, Tesla nearly surpassed their total vehicle sales in 2020 with <b>473,136</b> vehicle sales.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-sales-in-us">Tesla sales in the US</h2>
<p>The Tesla Model Y was the most popular electric vehicle in the US ranked by a number of deliveries in Q1 2021. <strong>48,364</strong> Model Y vehicles were delivered in the first quarter of 2021. Tesla Model 3 claims second place with <strong>26,983</strong> quarterly deliveries in the country.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-sales-in-china">Tesla sales in China</h2>
<p>As of August 2021, the Tesla Model 3 was the second most sold plug-in vehicle in China. A total of <b>92,755</b> Model 3s and <b>59,900 </b>Model Ys have been sold throughout the year.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-sales-in-europe">Tesla sales in Europe</h2>
<p>At the end of August 2021, the Tesla Model 3 was the most sold plug-in vehicle in Europe. <strong>76,440 vehicles</strong> have been sold across the continent. That’s <strong>71.29%</strong> more than the most popular EV model in Europe, the Volkswagen ID.3.</p>

<h2 class="text-center" id="tesla-employees">How many people work at Tesla?</h2>

<p>I’d also be happy to answer any questions you may have about the data you’ve read here. And I always love suggestions about how to make these roundups even better.</p>

    Using beautiful soup extract the table with Tesla Quarterly Revenue and store it into a dataframe named tesla_revenue. The dataframe should have columns Date and Revenue. Make sure the comma and dollar sign is removed from the Revenue column.

    In [ ]:
    import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd
# Replace 'your_url_here' with the actual URL of the web page you want to scrape
url = 'https://backlinko.com/tesla-stats'

# Send an HTTP GET request to the URL
response = requests.get(url)

# Parse the HTML content of the page
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')

tesla_revenue = []

for table in soup.find_all('table'):
    if table.find('th').getText().startswith("Year"):
        for row in table.find("tbody").find_all("tr"):
            col = row.find_all("td")
            if len(col) != 2:
                continue
            Date = col[0].text
            revenue = col[1].text.replace("$", "").replace(",", "")
            tesla_revenue.append({"Year": Date, "Revenue": revenue})

# Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
tesla_revenue_df = pd.DataFrame(tesla_revenue)

# Display the first few rows of the DataFrame
print(tesla_revenue_df.tail())

        Year Revenue
37  2016   17782
38  2017   37543
39  2018   48817
40  2019   48016
41  2020   70757

    Cleaning the data

    In [ ]:
    import pandas as pd
# Check if the "Revenue" column is not empty
not_empty = tesla_revenue_df["Revenue"] != ""
filtered_rows = tesla_revenue_df[
    tesla_revenue_df['Revenue'].str.contains('[a-zA-Z]') & (tesla_revenue_df['Revenue'].str.len() > 6)]
# If not_empty is True, drop rows with empty values; otherwise, filter only non-empty rows
if not_empty.any():
    tesla_revenue_df["Revebye"] = tesla_revenue_df["Revenue"].str[:5]
    filtered_rows = filtered_rows[not_empty]
else:
    print("No rows with non-empty 'Revenue' values found.")
# Display the updated DataFrame
print(filtered_rows)

    ANS 3: Using yfinance to Extract Stock Data of GME

    ¶

    Using the Ticker function enter the ticker symbol of the stock we want to extract data on to create a ticker object. The stock is GameStop and its ticker symbol is GME.

    In [ ]:
    gme = yf.Ticker('GME')

    Using the ticker object and the function history extract stock information and save it in a dataframe named gme_data. Set the period parameter to max so we get information for the maximum amount of time.

    In [ ]:
    gme_data = gme.history(period = "max")

    Reset the index using the reset_index(inplace=True) function on the gme_data DataFrame and display the first five rows of the gme_data dataframe using the head function. Take a screenshot of the results and code from the beginning of Question 3 to the results below.

    In [ ]:
    gme_data.reset_index(inplace=True)
gme_data.head(5)

    In [ ]:
    url1 = "https://www.companiesmarketcap.com/gamestop/revenue"
html_data1 = requests.get(url1).text
soup2=BeautifulSoup(html_data1,"html.parser")
print(soup2.prettify)

<h1>Revenue for GameStop
(GME)</h1>
<h2><strong>Revenue in 2023 (TTM): <span class="background-ya">$5.81 B</span></strong></h2>
<p class="mt-2">
According to <strong>GameStop
</strong>'s latest financial reports the company's current revenue (TTM) is <strong>$5.81 B</strong>.
In 2022 the company made a revenue of <strong>$5.95 B</strong> an increase over the years 2021 revenue that were of <strong>$5.87 B</strong>.The revenue is the total amount of income that a company generates by the sale of goods or services. Unlike with the <a href="/gamestop/earnings/">earnings</a> no expenses are subtracted.
</p>
<div>
<h2 class="big">Revenue history for GameStop
from 2002 to 2023</h2>
<svg class="companiesmarketcap-chart" height="550" id="marketcapchart" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"></svg>
</div>
<h3>Annual revenue</h3>
<div style="overflow-y: scroll;">
<table class="table" style="width:100%">

<h4><a href="/lexicon/market-cap-of-a-company/">What is the market capitalization of a company?</a></h4>
<p>The market capitalization sometimes referred as Marketcap, is the value of a publicly listed company.<br/>
In most cases it can be easily calculated by multiplying the share price with the amount of outstanding shares.</p>

    import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import pandas as pd

# Replace 'your_url_here' with the actual URL of the web page you want to scrape
url1 = 'https://companiesmarketcap.com/gamestop/revenue/'

# Send an HTTP GET request to the URL
response2 = requests.get(url1).text

# Parse the HTML content of the page
soup2 = BeautifulSoup(response2, 'html.parser')

gme_revenue = []
for table in soup2.find_all('table'):
    if table.find('th').getText().startswith("Year"):
        for row in table.find("tbody").find_all("tr"):
            col = row.find_all("td")
            if len(col) != 3:
                continue
            Date = col[0].text
            revenue = col[1].text.replace("$", "").replace(",", "")
            gme_revenue.append({"Year": Date, "Revenue": revenue})

# Create a DataFrame from the list of dictionaries
gme_revenue_df = pd.DataFrame(gme_revenue)

# Display the first few rows of the DataFrame
print(gme_revenue_df.head())

             Year Revenue
0  2023 (TTM)  5.81 B
1        2022  5.95 B
2        2021  5.87 B
3        2020  5.16 B
4        2019  7.33 B

fig.show()
